Using Technical Indicators

Quantitative trading strategies often use various technical indicators, to identify patterns that are emerging in the prices.

Technical indicators can be used to either indicate an emerging price trend, or to indicate that prices have reached an extreme high or low value, and that they may be about to revert.

The SMA, EMA, MACD, Z-Score, and RSI are examples of popular technical indicators.

The technical indicators are calculated from the recent stock prices and returns.

The Simple Moving Average (SMA)

The Simple Moving Average (SMA) price \(p^{SMA}_i\) is the average of the past prices \(p_{i-j}\) over a look-back window of length \(L\):

\[{\normalsize p^{SMA}_i = \frac{1}{L} \sum\limits_{j=0}^{L-1} p_{i-j}}\] The parameter \(L\) is equal to the length of the look-back window.

The drawback of the SMA is that it applies the same weight to the recent and past prices.

Its calculation also requires maintaining a buffer (queue) of past prices, with the length equal to the look-back parameter \(L\).

> library(dygraphs, quietly=TRUE)
> library(lubridate, quietly=TRUE)

> dygraph(xtsv, main = "DAX Index (log)") %>% 
+   dyRangeSelector()

How to Include Images

Image files can be loaded and displayed by using the following markdown syntax:
![animated_gif](image/chi_squared.gif)

The image file should be either in the same directory as the R Markdown file, or in a sub-directory.

Plots in Two-column Layout Using CSS Code

The Normal probability density function is given by: \[ P(x) = \frac{e^{-(x-\mu)^2/2\sigma^2}}{\sigma\sqrt{2 \pi}} \] Code for plotting the Normal probability density function:

> # Plot a Normal probability distribution
> curve(expr=dnorm(x, sd=1.5), type="l", xlim=c(-5, 5),
+       xlab="", ylab="", lwd=2, col="blue", 
+       main="Normal Density Function")
> # Draw shaded area
> xvar <- seq(-5, 5, length=100)
> yvar <- dnorm(xvar, mean=0.0, sd=1.5)
> startd <- 2; endd <- 3
> subv <- ((xvar >= startd) & (xvar <= endd))
> polygon(c(startd, xvar[subv], endd),
+         c(-1, yvar[subv], -1), col="red")

Slide with HTML Widget

Below is a network graph created using the D3.js JavaScript library embedded as an HTML widget.

> data(MisLinks, MisNodes)
> forceNetwork(Links=MisLinks, Nodes=MisNodes, 
+   Source="source", Target="target", Value="value", 
+   NodeID="name", Group="group", opacity=0.8)
